upports.\r\n\r\nReactive UI\'s & UI Performance in Meteor\r\n\r\nPaul van Zyl, CTO at Nona Creative and Meteor fanBoy, will be talking about some experiments, and performance techniques to squeeze the most out of meteor, blaze and javascript, with a particular focus on mobile optimisation, and a few lessons learnt.\r\n\r\nLightning Talks (Short and Informal)\r\n\r\nElan Schnider - - Co-founder of Swiss-based app company, \'Roadtripz\' and a specialist in UIUX Design - Elan has a passion for all things digital and a great love for startups. Elan will be speaking about his new startup built on Meteor.\r\n\r\nAnyone is welcome to pitch a 5 to 7-minute lightning talk on something they\'vebuilt, or something they\'re building. We\'d love to see it.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSponsor Nona Creative (Venue & Beer)\r\n\r\nNona Creative is an ambitious digital studio in Cape Town, South Africa, with a small team, a big heart and clients on five continents.\r\n\r\nTopic Speakers Welcome - We\'re Always on the hunt for speakers, if you\'d like to talk at this meetup or another, let us know and we\'ll set it up.\r\n\r\nElan Schnider - Co-founder of Swiss-based app company, \'Roadtripz \' and a specialist in UIUX Design - Elan has a passion for all things digital and a great love for startups.','<p>This month we\'ll be focused on user interfaces in javascript and meteor, and tackle questions of approach and performance for web and hybrid apps, looking at how to get started with writing better UI\'s, and some of the possibilities that Meteor Supports.</p>\n<p>Reactive UI\'s &amp; UI Performance in Meteor</p>\n<p>Paul van Zyl, CTO at Nona Creative and Meteor fanBoy, will be talking about some experiments, and performance techniques to squeeze the most out of meteor, blaze and javascript, with a particular focus on mobile optimisation, and a few lessons learnt.</p>\n<p>Lightning Talks (Short and Informal)</p>\n<p>Elan Schnider - - Co-founder of Swiss-based app company, \'Roadtripz\' and a specialist in UIUX Design - Elan has a passion for all things digital and a great love for startups. Elan will be speaking about his new startup built on Meteor.</p>\n<p>Anyone is welcome to pitch a 5 to 7-minute lightning talk on something they\'vebuilt, or something they\'re building. We\'d love to see it.</p>\n<p>Sponsor Nona Creative (Venue &amp; Beer)</p>\n<p>Nona Creative is an ambitious digital studio in Cape Town, South Africa, with a small team, a big heart and clients on five continents.</p>\n<p>Topic Speakers Welcome - We\'re Always on the hunt for speakers, if you\'d like to talk at this meetup or another, let us know and we\'ll set it up.</p>\n<p>Elan Schnider - Co-founder of Swiss-based app company, \'Roadtripz \' and a specialist in UIUX Design - Elan has a passion for all things digital and a great love for startups.</p>\n','2016-03-16','18:00:00','20:30:00','Western Cape','Cape Town','','Old Castle Brewery, Beach Rd, Woodstock, Cape Town, 7915, South Africa','-33.9248885','18.44773609999993','https://maps.google.com/?q=Old+Castle+Brewery&ftid=0x1dcc5d99a8bcd1cb:0x76681ae213743dc1','http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Cape-Town/events/228945604',502,'2016-03-08 12:08:54',0,'2017-12-07 10:28:54'),(42,1,'Steve Barnett - Progressive Enhancement','steve-barnett-progressive-enhancement','info@nodeza.co.za','','Making things for the web is hard: it\'s a hostile environment with lots of variation in things like browsers, network speed and ','Steve Barnett - Progressive Enhancement\r\n\r\nMaking things for the web is hard: it\'s a hostile environment with lots of variation in things like browsers, network speed and quality, and disabilities of our users. I\'ll be talking about Progressive Enhancement (PE): a way of thinking about and building web apps that puts our users first. Building with PE gives us ways to handle our smörgåsbord of unknowns, using Human-Centered Design thinking.\r\n\r\nI\'ll talk about what PE is, why it\'s important, and how to get the rest of your team (and the boss) on board. We\'ll discuss the assumptions and choices that we developers make, and how the cost of that gets passed on to our users. I\'ll also touch briefly on how PE links up with Responsive Web Design, modern Front-end Performance best practices, and JavaScript frameworks (like Meteor).\r\n\r\nAbout Steve Barnett\r\n\r\nSteve Barnett works as a code mentor at Project codeX, and as a freelance Front-end developer and User Experience person. He’s a bit addicted to meetups: you can find him helping out with RailsBridge Cape Town or Cape Town Front-End Developers. If he’s not there, he’s probably crouched in an awkward position in front of something funny-looking, taking pictures of it.\r\n\r\nYou can find him on Twitter as @maxbarners, on GitHub as SteveBarnett, and on his own site Naga (which really, really, needs a redesign) as, erm, himself.\r\n\r\nSponsor Nona Creative (Venue, AV & Beer)\r\n\r\nNona Creative is an ambitious digital studio in Cape Town, South Africa, with a small team, a big heart and clients on five continents.\r\n\r\nTopic Speakers Welcome - We\'re Always on the hunt for speakers, if you\'d like to talk at this meetup or another, let us know and we\'ll set it up.','<p>Steve Barnett - Progressive Enhancement</p>\n<p>Making things for the web is hard: it\'s a hostile environment with lots of variation in things like browsers, network speed and quality, and disabilities of our users. I\'ll be talking about Progressive Enhancement (PE): a way of thinking about and building web apps that puts our users first. Building with PE gives us ways to handle our smörgåsbord of unknowns, using Human-Centered Design thinking.</p>\n<p>I\'ll talk about what PE is, why it\'s important, and how to get the rest of your team (and the boss) on board. We\'ll discuss the assumptions and choices that we developers make, and how the cost of that gets passed on to our users. I\'ll also touch briefly on how PE links up with Responsive Web Design, modern Front-end Performance best practices, and JavaScript frameworks (like Meteor).</p>\n<p>About Steve Barnett</p>\n<p>Steve Barnett works as a code mentor at Project codeX, and as a freelance Front-end developer and User Experience person. He’s a bit addicted to meetups: you can find him helping out with RailsBridge Cape Town or Cape Town Front-End Developers. If he’s not there, he’s probably crouched in an awkward position in front of something funny-looking, taking pictures of it.</p>\n<p>You can find him on Twitter as @maxbarners, on GitHub as SteveBarnett, and on his own site Naga (which really, really, needs a redesign) as, erm, himself.</p>\n<p>Sponsor Nona Creative (Venue, AV &amp; Beer)</p>\n<p>Nona Creative is an ambitious digital studio in Cape Town, South Africa, with a small team, a big heart and clients on five continents.</p>\n<p>Topic Speakers Welcome - We\'re Always on the hunt for speakers, if you\'d like to talk at this meetup or another, let us know and we\'ll set it up.</p>\n','2016-04-20','18:00:00','21:00:00','Western Cape','Cape Town','','Old Castle Brewery, Beach Rd, Woodstock, Cape Town, 7915, South Africa','-33.9248885','18.44773609999993','https://maps.google.com/?q=Old+Castle+Brewery&ftid=0x1dcc5d99a8bcd1cb:0x76681ae213743dc1','http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Cape-Town/events/229419968/',479,'2016-04-05 12:39:21',0,'2017-12-11 05:10:19'),(43,1,'The Journey of a Package','the-journey-of-a-package','info@nodeza.com','','This month we\'ll be telling the story of a package developer, and looking at how you can deploy free package demos with Heroku.','This month we\'ll be telling the story of a package developer, and looking at how you can deploy free package demos with Heroku.  Check out our speakers:\r\n\r\n------ \r\n\r\n### Paul van Zyl\r\n\r\nA long time lover of bright lights, loud noises, and shiny magic boxes,  I\'m now a co-founder and the CTO at Nona Creative,  a digital consultancy based in Cape Town, South Africa. \r\n\r\n### Free Meteor Hosting with Heroku and MLAB\r\n\r\nWith all the hype about Galaxy, meteor\'s free hosting quietly went away. While it\'s great to have galaxy, it is a little expensive for quickly putting up an open source demo of your latest package, or testing out that idea with a hosted environment. \r\n\r\n------\r\n\r\n### Jaco Swarts \r\n\r\n co-organizer of the Meteor Cape Town meetup, team lead at EdgeCase Software where they build real estate solutions. He\'s also a javascript enthusiast and freelances on meteor projects in his spare time.\r\n\r\n\r\n> In-place CMS for static websites - a package building journey\r\n\r\nI recently completed a single-page static website for a local business, but wanted to take it to the next level and introduce i18n translation as well as simple content management functionality for the client. Instead of switching to WordPress, I decided to roll my own with Meteor. This is a show and tell talk of that journey. \r\n\r\n\r\nBeer & AV Sponsored by nona creative. [nonacreative.com](https://nonacreative.com)','<p>This month we\'ll be telling the story of a package developer, and looking at how you can deploy free package demos with Heroku.  Check out our speakers:</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Paul van Zyl</h3>\n<p>A long time lover of bright lights, loud noises, and shiny magic boxes,  I\'m now a co-founder and the CTO at Nona Creative,  a digital consultancy based in Cape Town, South Africa.</p>\n<h3>Free Meteor Hosting with Heroku and MLAB</h3>\n<p>With all the hype about Galaxy, meteor\'s free hosting quietly went away. While it\'s great to have galaxy, it is a little expensive for quickly putting up an open source demo of your latest package, or testing out that idea with a hosted environment.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Jaco Swarts</h3>\n<p>co-organizer of the Meteor Cape Town meetup, team lead at EdgeCase Software where they build real estate solutions. He\'s also a javascript enthusiast and freelances on meteor projects in his spare time.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In-place CMS for static websites - a package building journey</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I recently completed a single-page static website for a local business, but wanted to take it to the next level and introduce i18n translation as well as simple content management functionality for the client. Instead of switching to WordPress, I decided to roll my own with Meteor. This is a show and tell talk of that journey.</p>\n<p>Beer &amp; AV Sponsored by nona creative. <a href=\"https://nonacreative.com\">nonacreative.com</a></p>\n','2016-05-18','18:00:00','20:00:00','Western Cape','Cape Town','','Old Castle Brewery, Lower Church St, Woodstock, Cape Town, 7915, South Africa','-33.925004','18.448434799999973','https://maps.google.com/?q=Old+Castle+Brewery&ftid=0x1dcc5d98554440cf:0xbbec9c7db542b080','http://www.meetup.com/Meteor-Cape-Town/events/230710231',429,'2016-05-17 11:44:32',1,'2017-12-07 10:28:43'),(44,1,'Have a meetup','have-a-meetup','info@nodeza.co.za','','Hi Node Users, Time to meet and greet!','Hi Node Users, Time to meet and greet!\r\n\r\nThe idea is to have a mostly free-form meetup - just as an introduction to the community and to share what you are doing with Node, or what you would like to use Node for, or just if you are curious about Node and would like to pick the brains of people who have already travelled this path :)\r\n\r\nWe will have a short talk on Middleware and Callbacks to start us off.  \r\n\r\nIf you have anything you\'d like to present / hear about at a Node meetup, please send through an email to Len or Bradley and we\'ll make it happen! You\'re also welcome to do a lightning talk on the day. \r\n\r\nPizza and beer provided!','<p>Hi Node Users, Time to meet and greet!</p>\n<p>The idea is to have a mostly free-form meetup - just as an introduction to the community and to share what you are doing with Node, or what you would like to use Node for, or just if you are curious about Node and would like to pick the brains of people who have already tr