 Server Side Rendering - What is the point? \r\n\r\n  > Gergana Young ([@gerybbg](https://twitter.com/gerybbg)) \r\n\r\nOne of the latest SPA crazes, server side rendering. Should we be using it? Why do we need it? How do we do it? \r\n\r\n### The What, Why and How of React Native \r\n  \r\n  > Pat Kayongo ([@PatKayongo](https://twitter.com/PatKayongo)) \r\n\r\nBuilding mobile applications for multiple platforms has always been an expensive challenge. The talk walks through React Native, Facebook\'s answer to this problem, with a live demo of how it works. \r\n\r\n### Open Floor / Show-and-Tell / Code critique: \r\n\r\nLike open-mic night except for JavaScript. Do you have something cool that you want to share, or get some feedback on? A specific problem that you\'re not quite sure how to solve, or just want some community code review? This is the time!\r\n\r\nLet your hair down, figuratively or literally, and let\'s just talk about code.','<h3>Agenda:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>18:30 - Introduction</li>\n<li>18:45 - Lightning Talk (15 mins) - Gergana Young (@gerybbg)</li>\n<li>19:00 - Talk (45 mins) - Pat Kayongo (@PatKayongo)</li>\n<li>19:45 - Food, Open Floor / Show-and-Tell / Code critique.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Server Side Rendering - What is the point?</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Gergana Young (<a href=\"https://twitter.com/gerybbg\">@gerybbg</a>)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>One of the latest SPA crazes, server side rendering. Should we be using it? Why do we need it? How do we do it?</p>\n<h3>The What, Why and How of React Native</h3>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Pat Kayongo (<a href=\"https://twitter.com/PatKayongo\">@PatKayongo</a>)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Building mobile applications for multiple platforms has always been an expensive challenge. The talk walks through React Native, Facebook\'s answer to this problem, with a live demo of how it works.</p>\n<h3>Open Floor / Show-and-Tell / Code critique:</h3>\n<p>Like open-mic night except for JavaScript. Do you have something cool that you want to share, or get some feedback on? A specific problem that you\'re not quite sure how to solve, or just want some community code review? This is the time!</p>\n<p>Let your hair down, figuratively or literally, and let\'s just talk about code.</p>\n','2017-04-20','06:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/238823185/',348,'2017-04-18 05:59:17',NULL,'2017-12-12 18:22:55'),(53,1,'Jozi.JS June Meetup - Everything is a work-in-progress','jozi-js-june-meetup-everything-is-a-work-in-progress','info@nodeza.co.za','','Breaking your promises : Async control flow patterns ','### Agenda: \r\n\r\n - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n\r\n - 19:00 - Lightning Talk (TBD)\r\n\r\n - 19:15 - Breaking your promises : Async control flow patterns - Ryan Kotzen (@eXigentCoder)\r\n\r\n - 20:00 - More blah blah\r\n\r\nBreaking your promises : Async control flow patterns \r\n\r\nRyan Kotzen (@eXigentCoder)\r\n\r\nWhen calling asynchronous JavaScript functions the order in which your code gets executed (control flow) becomes critical but it doesn\'t need to be confusing. In this talk we will explore a variety of solutions to the control flow problem from callbacks all the way up to async-await.','<h3>Agenda:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>18:30 - Food and blah blah</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>19:00 - Lightning Talk (TBD)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>19:15 - Breaking your promises : Async control flow patterns - Ryan Kotzen (@eXigentCoder)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>20:00 - More blah blah</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Breaking your promises : Async control flow patterns</p>\n<p>Ryan Kotzen (@eXigentCoder)</p>\n<p>When calling asynchronous JavaScript functions the order in which your code gets executed (control flow) becomes critical but it doesn\'t need to be confusing. In this talk we will explore a variety of solutions to the control flow problem from callbacks all the way up to async-await.</p>\n','2017-06-22','18:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/240205057',200,'2017-07-20 02:49:27',NULL,'2017-12-12 18:19:44'),(54,1,'Jozi.JS July Meetup - care deeply','jozi-js-july-meetup-care-deeply','info@nodeza.co.za','',' Introduction to Elm ','### Introduction to Elm \r\n\r\nGuillaume Belrose (@gbelrose)\r\n\r\nIn this Meetup, I will be giving an introduction to Elm (http://elm-lang.org). \r\n\r\nElm is a delightful and easy to learn Functional Programming language focused on front-end web applications. It has a Haskell-like syntax and was designed from the ground up to be super user friendly. It is also super robust and allows you to scale to large codebase without too much fuss. For example, NoRedInk, a San Francisco based startup has a[masked] LOC codebase and so far has hit 1 runtime error in 6 months into production. \r\n\r\nI\'ll be talking about Functional Programming, the language syntax, the Virtual DOM, and the Elm Architecture which is the approach that Elm takes for writing user interfaces (displaying things, handling states).\r\n\r\nWe are going to write code that run the 1st time it compile, I can\'t however guarantee that it is going to look good. ','<h3>Introduction to Elm</h3>\n<p>Guillaume Belrose (@gbelrose)</p>\n<p>In this Meetup, I will be giving an introduction to Elm (http://elm-lang.org).</p>\n<p>Elm is a delightful and easy to learn Functional Programming language focused on front-end web applications. It has a Haskell-like syntax and was designed from the ground up to be super user friendly. It is also super robust and allows you to scale to large codebase without too much fuss. For example, NoRedInk, a San Francisco based startup has a[masked] LOC codebase and so far has hit 1 runtime error in 6 months into production.</p>\n<p>I\'ll be talking about Functional Programming, the language syntax, the Virtual DOM, and the Elm Architecture which is the approach that Elm takes for writing user interfaces (displaying things, handling states).</p>\n<p>We are going to write code that run the 1st time it compile, I can\'t however guarantee that it is going to look good.</p>\n','2017-07-20','18:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/241082269',255,'2017-07-20 02:52:35',NULL,'2017-12-13 18:10:35'),(55,1,'Jozi.JS August Meetup','jozi-js-august-meetup','info@nodeza.co.za','0729589367','#### Agenda: \r\n\r\n - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n\r\n - 19:00 - Something about VueJS - Aadil Cachalia\r\n\r\n - 19:15 - Intro to WebAs','#### Something about VueJS\r\n\r\n*Aadil Cachalia*\r\n\r\nA brief exploration of Vue through a side by side comparison with Angular and React. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Intro to WebAssembly \r\n\r\n*Len Weincier* (@lenwnc)\r\n\r\nWe lift the lid a little and take a look at the upcoming WebAssembly standard and try to understand what it means for us all. What is WASM and where is it headed ? Will it affect us ? Is it the future of a multi language web ? Is it the end of Javascript ? ','<h4>Something about VueJS</h4>\n<p><em>Aadil Cachalia</em></p>\n<p>A brief exploration of Vue through a side by side comparison with Angular and React.</p>\n<h4>Intro to WebAssembly</h4>\n<p><em>Len Weincier</em> (@lenwnc)</p>\n<p>We lift the lid a little and take a look at the upcoming WebAssembly standard and try to understand what it means for us all. What is WASM and where is it headed ? Will it affect us ? Is it the future of a multi language web ? Is it the end of Javascript ?</p>\n','2017-08-24','06:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/241082311',58,'2017-11-09 08:08:07',NULL,'2017-12-12 21:14:55'),(56,1,'Jozi.JS September Meetup - Here comes the sun','jozi-js-september-meetup-here-comes-the-sun','info@nodeza.co.za','0729589367','#### Agenda:\r\n  - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n\r\n  - 19:00 - Let\'s overreact about React - Melissa Landsman (@MelissaLands1)\r\n\r\n ','#### Let\'s overreact about React\r\n\r\n*Melissa Landsman* (@MelissaLands1)\r\n\r\nI will be explaining an intro on how to get started with react and Facebook code. Tools that are available as well as yeoman. Why its not always the best approach to use generated systems for react components.\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Going cold-turkey on JQuery\r\n\r\n*Nelson Pascoal* (@foomip)\r\n\r\nJQuery has been a great tool for helping us to manipulate the DOM. However when using web frameworks like React things can get a bit akward. Both JQuery and your web framework are expecting to be the only ones manipulating the DOM. Let’s look at some strategies for getting rid of the akwardness and finally removing JQuery from your life - may he rest in peace :) ','<h4>Let\'s overreact about React</h4>\n<p><em>Melissa Landsman</em> (@MelissaLands1)</p>\n<p>I will be explaining an intro on how to get started with react and Facebook code. Tools that are available as well as yeoman. Why its not always the best approach to use generated systems for react components.</p>\n<h4>Going cold-turkey on JQuery</h4>\n<p><em>Nelson Pascoal</em> (@foomip)</p>\n<p>JQuery has been a great tool for helping us to manipulate the DOM. However when using web frameworks like React things can get a bit akward. Both JQuery and your web framework are expecting to be the only ones manipulating the DOM. Let’s look at some strategies for getting rid of the akwardness and finally removing JQuery from your life - may he rest in peace :)</p>\n','2017-09-21','18:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/243082621',95,'2017-11-09 08:18:34',NULL,'2017-12-12 21:14:57'),(57,1,'Jozi.JS October Meetup - It\'s never too late to start','jozi-js-october-meetup-its-never-too-late-to-start','info@nodeza.co.za','0729589367','#### Agenda: \r\n\r\n - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n\r\n - 19:00 - So what is Polymer, anyway? - Mike Geyser (@mikegeyser)\r\n\r\n - 19:15','#### So what is Polymer, anyway?\r\n\r\n*Mike Geyser* (@mikegeyser)\r\n\r\nPolymer is not just a framework, it is an ambitious attempt to scry into the future and inform the present - to steward and direct the evolution of the Web Platform. \r\n\r\nThis talk will give a brief overview of Polymer 3.0, the direction of WebComponents and make a case for why you should care about Polymer and the direction of the Web Platform. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n#### gRPC: an Alternative to the REST? \r\n\r\n*Pieter Louw* (@pieterlouw) \r\n\r\nWhile our public API’s these days are mainly REST,it has become possible to expose our services through gRPC in addition to REST.\r\n\r\nJoin this journey to see what gRPC is and in what ways it can improve your API and/or internal service communications. ','<h4>So what is Polymer, anyway?</h4>\n<p><em>Mike Geyser</em> (@mikegeyser)</p>\n<p>Polymer is not just a framework, it is an ambitious attempt to scry into the future and inform the present - to steward and direct the evolution of the Web Platform.</p>\n<p>This talk will give a brief overview of Polymer 3.0, the direction of WebComponents and make a case for why you should care about Polymer and the direction of the Web Platform.</p>\n<h4>gRPC: an Alternative to the REST?</h4>\n<p><em>Pieter Louw</em> (@pieterlouw)</p>\n<p>While our public API’s these days are mainly REST,it has become possible to expose our services through gRPC in addition to REST.</p>\n<p>Join this journey to see what gRPC is and in what ways it can improve your API and/or internal service communications.</p>\n','2017-10-19','18:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/243167225',91,'2017-11-09 08:20:58',NULL,'2017-12-12 21:14:59'),(58,1,'Jozi.JS November Meetup - Indistinguishable from magic','jozi-js-november-meetup-indistinguishable-from-magic','info@nodeza.co.za','0729589367','#### Agenda: \r\n\r\n - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n\r\n - 19:00 - Styled Components - Peter Gwaka (@peter_gwaka)\r\n\r\n - 19:15 - Useful','#### Styled Components\r\n\r\n*Peter Gwaka* (@peter_gwaka)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Useful bits: a medley of tips for effective full-stack JavaScript development\r\n\r\n*Rouan Wilsenach* (@rouanw)\r\n\r\nRouan will host an interactive session where the audience can pick from a few short discussion/demo topics, including security, code style, simplifying single page apps, database performance, server-side page composition, and microservice communication.','<h4>Styled Components</h4>\n<p><em>Peter Gwaka</em> (@peter_gwaka)</p>\n<h4>Useful bits: a medley of tips for effective full-stack JavaScript development</h4>\n<p><em>Rouan Wilsenach</em> (@rouanw)</p>\n<p>Rouan will host an interactive session where the audience can pick from a few short discussion/demo topics, including security, code style, simplifying single page apps, database performance, server-side page composition, and microservice communication.</p>\n','2017-11-23','18:30:00',NULL,'Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 Newtown Ave, Killarney, Johannesburg, 2193, South Africa','-26.1696199','28.05246999999997','https://maps.google.com/?q=1+Newtown+Ave,+Killarney,+Johannesburg,+2193,+South+Africa&ftid=0x1e950c45e1ca664f:0xf9f367c83adeedc6','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/243167240',183,'2017-11-09 08:23:34',NULL,'2017-12-12 21:15:00'),(59,1,'January.Jozi.js: Nothing ventured, nothing gained','january-jozi-js-nothing-ventured-nothing-gained','info@nodeza.co.za','0729589367','Kick the year into gear with the first Jozi.JS of the year! We\'ll be starting proceedings with two talks, a lightning talk.','Kick the year into gear with the first Jozi.JS of the year! We\'ll be starting proceedings with two talks, a lightning talk (still TBD) and then an investigation into web bluetooth with @gerybbg. Come along for some beer, pizza and JavaScript!\r\n\r\n(*or analogous celebratory beverage)\r\n\r\nAgenda:\r\n - 18:30 - Food and blah blah\r\n - 19:00 - Lightning Talk (TBC)\r\n - 19:15 - A Web of Things - Gery Young (@gerybbg)\r\n - 20:00 - More blah blah\r\n\r\n#### A Web of Things - Gery Young (@gerybbg):\r\n\r\nDevices, smart devices everywhere. This is what our world is turning into. Your car tells you how to drive, your watch tells you when to exercise, and your phone tells you when you are hungry. OK, maybe that last bit is a little over the top, but I’m sure someone will make an app like that soon. All of this is controlled by applications which use Bluetooth and Wi-Fi to connect and communicate with each other. However, this is never enough for us as developers, we need to be in control.\r\n\r\nThe Chrome dev team started the Physical Web movement with the intention of making everything smarter. With Web Bluetooth we can control almost any Bluetooth Low Energy device from a website. No longer dependent on the platform we are using or on apps which require installation or updates. All we need is a browser which supports it.\r\n\r\nThis talk will cover some of the fundamental concepts of connecting to BLE devices using Chrome, including some privacy and security considerations. Using the Angular Web Bluetooth module we will create and deploy a website and show how anyone can easily connect to a bluetooth device just by opening their web browser.','<p>Kick the year into gear with the first Jozi.JS of the year! We\'ll be starting proceedings with two talks, a lightning talk (still TBD) and then an investigation into web bluetooth with @gerybbg. Come along for some beer, pizza and JavaScript!</p>\n<p>(*or analogous celebratory beverage)</p>\n<p>Agenda:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>18:30 - Food and blah blah</li>\n<li>19:00 - Lightning Talk (TBC)</li>\n<li>19:15 - A Web of Things - Gery Young (@gerybbg)</li>\n<li>20:00 - More blah blah</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>A Web of Things - Gery Young (@gerybbg):</h4>\n<p>Devices, smart devices everywhere. This is what our world is turning into. Your car tells you how to drive, your watch tells you when to exercise, and your phone tells you when you are hungry. OK, maybe that last bit is a little over the top, but I’m sure someone will make an app like that soon. All of this is controlled by applications which use Bluetooth and Wi-Fi to connect and communicate with each other. However, this is never enough for us as developers, we need to be in control.</p>\n<p>The Chrome dev team started the Physical Web movement with the intention of making everything smarter. With Web Bluetooth we can control almost any Bluetooth Low Energy device from a website. No longer dependent on the platform we are using or on apps which require installation or updates. All we need is a browser which supports it.</p>\n<p>This talk will cover some of the fundamental concepts of connecting to BLE devices using Chrome, including some privacy and security considerations. Using the Angular Web Bluetooth module we will create and deploy a website and show how anyone can easily connect to a bluetooth device just by opening their web browser.</p>\n','2018-01-18','18:30:00','21:30:00','Gauteng','Johannesburg','Killarney','1 ','-26.1696199','28.05247','','https://www.meetup.com/Jozi-JS/events/245751778',135,'2017-12-14 04:36:11',NULL,'2017-12-14 04:36:11');
